,"Phrenic nerve","Anterior cutaneous nerve","Greater splanchnic nerves"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ephrenic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E provides sensory innervation to the fibrous pericardium of the heart. This nerve originates from the cervical plexus (C3-C5) and descends through the thorax to innervate the diaphragm and provide sensory fibres to the fibrous pericardium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evagus nerve\u003C/strong\u003E provides parasympathetic innervation to the heart but does not supply the fibrous pericardium. \u003Cstrong\u003EIntercostal nerves\u003C/strong\u003E supply the chest wall and pleura but not the pericardium. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior cutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is a branch of the intercostal nerve that supplies the skin of the anterior chest wall. The \u003Cstrong\u003Egreater splanchnic nerves\u003C/strong\u003E carry sympathetic fibres to the thoracic and abdominal viscera but do not provide sensory innervation to the fibrous pericardium.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The phrenic nerve provides sensory innervation to the fibrous pericardium of the heart."],"references":["Netter, F. H. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: Classic Regional Approach-Ebook. 2022. Elsevier Health Sciences","Benzon, H., Raja, S. N., Fishman, S. E., Liu, S. S., \u0026 Cohen, S. P. Essentials of pain medicine. 2011. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44315"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14398"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44315"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-03T16:12:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-03T16:13:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7093"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58906